name: pyruvic aldehyde dimethyl acetal

Acetals generally increase the melting point due to their ability to form a rigid cyclic structure, which can add approximately +30°C. Each methyl group adds non-polarity and more mass, which usually increases the melting point by about +3°C for each group. However, the presence of the pyruvate moiety, which contains a carbonyl group attached to an additional methyl group, may have opposing effects; it can increase the melting point due to increased rigidity and molecular weight, while also potentially decreasing it due to the polar carbonyl group disrupting crystal packing. We will suppose an overall effect of the pyruvate group to be +7°C given these competing considerations. Adding these changes together gives us the predicted melting point.
